                			<p>
                				<span style="font-size:x-large"><b><a>F</a></b></span>orests provide a large number of products such as fruit, seed, resin, medicine, honey, cane and bark all defined as non-timber forest products (NTFPs). Such products have been collected incessantly from the forests for commercial use. Constant and large-scale collection of such products causes destruction of the habitat and deprives wildlife of their food sources. For example gooseberries that are harvested during summer are an important source of nutrients for sambar, chital, wild pig, elephant, langur and several other species. Human extraction of such products will deprive these species of their much needed nutrients during summer periods. 
                			</p>
                			<p>
                				NTFP Harvesting methods also have a severe impact on forests. Most times entire branches or trees are cut to harvest fruits or nuts killing the very source of these products. Forests are set on fire to collect deer antler that would otherwise be invisible on forest floor. 
                			</p>
                			<p>
                				It is scientifically proven that NTFP harvesting is not an economically viable profession while providing education is a better alternative for communities who are currently dependent on NTFP harvesting. 
